Ensure that your DataSource bean is properly configured to use HikariCP as the connection pool:

    @Configuration
    public class DatabaseConfig {

      @Bean
      public DataSource dataSource() {
          HikariDataSource dataSource = new HikariDataSource();
          // Configure Hikari pool properties, such as database URL, username, password, etc.
          return dataSource;
      }
    }

Use the `@Scope(&quot;prototype&quot;)` annotation on the connection handling class to create a new instance for each thread:

    @Component
    @Scope(&quot;prototype&quot;)
    public class ConnectionHandler {

      private Connection connection;

      public void openConnection() {
          // Logic to open the database connection
          // Use the DataSource to acquire a connection
          this.connection = dataSource.getConnection();
      }

      public void closeConnection() {
          // Logic to close the database connection
          if (this.connection != null) {
              try {
                  this.connection.close();
              } catch (SQLException e) {
                  // Handle connection closing exception if necessary
              }
          }
      }

    // Methods to handle the connection
    }

Use the `ThreadLocal` class to ensure that each thread gets its own instance of the `ConnectionHandler`:

    @Component
    public class ConnectionHandlerProvider {
      private ThreadLocal&lt;ConnectionHandler&gt; connectionHandlerThreadLocal = 
      new ThreadLocal&lt;&gt;();

      public ConnectionHandler getConnectionHandler() {
          ConnectionHandler connectionHandler = 
      connectionHandlerThreadLocal.get();
          if (connectionHandler == null) {
              connectionHandler = new ConnectionHandler();
              connectionHandler.openConnection();
              connectionHandlerThreadLocal.set(connectionHandler);
          }
          return connectionHandler;
      }

      public void releaseConnectionHandler() {
          ConnectionHandler connectionHandler = 
      connectionHandlerThreadLocal.get();
          if (connectionHandler != null) {
              connectionHandler.closeConnection();
              connectionHandlerThreadLocal.remove();
          }
      }
    }

When using the `ConnectionHandler`, obtain the instance from the `ConnectionHandlerProvider` and ensure that it is released after use:

    @Service
    public class MyService {

      @Autowired
      private ConnectionHandlerProvider connectionHandlerProvider;

      public void doSomethingWithConnection() {
          ConnectionHandler connectionHandler = 
      connectionHandlerProvider.getConnectionHandler();
          try {
              // Use the connection to execute queries or perform database 
      operations
          } finally {
              connectionHandlerProvider.releaseConnectionHandle();
          }
      }
    }

