I have dealt with the same problem - jobs ran just after resuming them from being paused.

Your workaround is useless for my situation, because it kills also jobs misfired because of full pool of executors (in that case, I really want these jobs to be executed as soon as some executor is available).

I found a better solution that works for me, although also not so elegant - unschedule the job schedule it again.

```java
void resumePausedJobAndDiscardMisfires(final JobDetail job, final Trigger trigger) {
    scheduler.unscheduleJob(trigger.getKey());
    scheduler.scheduleJob(job, Set.of(trigger), true);
    scheduler.rescheduleJob(trigger.getKey(), trigger);
}
```

Unscheduling the job really discards all it&#39;s misfires. I wish there could be some more straightforward solution, especially using the `rescheduleJob` method, one should be able to specify, if misfires should be dropped (which is the most wanted behaviour in the most cases IMHO).

Finally, also job deletion discards all misfires: `scheduler.deleteJob(jobKey);`.

